body:
As workaround, I bind CachedAction a customized implementation, which extends CachedAction by using SyncCacheApi. It works very well.

```
// In guice module
bind(CachedAction.class).to(SyncCachedAction.class);
```

```
public class SyncCachedAction extends CachedAction {

  private SyncCacheApi cacheApi;

  @Inject
  public SyncCachedAction(AsyncCacheApi asyncCacheApi, SyncCacheApi cacheApi) {
    super(asyncCacheApi);
    this.cacheApi = cacheApi;
  }

  public CompletionStage<Result> call(Http.Context ctx) {
    final String key = configuration.key();
    final Integer duration = configuration.duration();
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() ->
      cacheApi.getOrElseUpdate(key, () -> delegate.call(ctx).toCompletableFuture().get(), duration)
    );
  }

}
```

@richdougherty trying with the following versions and the error still happens:

```
java version "1.8.0_112"
Java(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build 1.8.0_112-b16)
Java HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 25.112-b16, mixed mode)
```
```
java version "1.8.0_121"
Java(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build 1.8.0_121-b13)
Java HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 25.121-b13, mixed mode)
```
I think the problem here is that we are moving between thread pools. Since `CacheAction` is not being specific about which thread pool should be used ([`thenComposeAsync` here](https://github.com/playframework/playframework/blob/master/framework/src/play-cache/src/main/java/play/cache/CachedAction.java#L30) uses a default thread pool, which is [`ForkJoinPool.commonPool`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ForkJoinPool.html#commonPool--)).

But, if you specify the `Executor`, then you won't need to fallback to `ForkJoinPool` which, as explained in the links you posted, is paranoid about SecurityManagers. The following works:

```java
public class MyCachedAction extends Action<MyCached> {

    private AsyncCacheApi cacheApi;
    private ExecutionContextExecutor executionContext;

    @Inject
    public MyCachedAction(AsyncCacheApi cacheApi, ExecutionContextExecutor executionContext) {
        this.cacheApi = cacheApi;
        this.executionContext = executionContext;
    }

    public CompletionStage<Result> call(Context ctx) {
        final String key = configuration.key();
        final Integer duration = configuration.duration();
        return cacheApi.<Result>get(key).thenComposeAsync(cacheResult -> {
            if (cacheResult != null) {
                return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(cacheResult);
            }
            return delegate.call(ctx).thenComposeAsync(result ->
                    cacheApi.set(key, result, duration).thenApply(ignore -> result)
            );
        }, executionContext);
    }

}
```
The only difference is that we are providing a thread pool explicitly.
